=== TASK ===
# Create Decision Page

## Overview
Build the Create Decision Page for Archject: a multi-step workflow (modal or full page) that enables users to create a Decision Card. Users can choose a template or start from scratch, add options (titles, descriptions, images/drawings, and default/recommended flags), attach files, set client recipients and reminder schedules, and preview the decision for client viewing. The page must integrate with the Decision Objects & Approval Workflow core, support centralized validation and error handling, and coordinate with file upload/management, CRUD operations, and project workspace context. The flow should support saving as a draft or publishing, which generates a client share link and sends/queues notifications.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A guided, multi-step interface to create a Decision Card within a specific Archject Project.
- Step 1: Template Selector – present a list of pre-built templates plus a “Start from scratch” option. Templates should define common decision patterns (e.g., finishes, layouts, change requests) and show a quick preview of included options.
- Step 2: Options Editor – allow adding, editing, and reordering decision options. Each option should support: title, description, image/ drawing attachments, and a “default” or “recommended” flag. Users can upload multiple images or attach files that illustrate the option.
- Step 3: Settings – configure the decision’s lifecycle: approval deadline, reminder schedule (e.g., days before deadline with recurrence options), whether the client must type a name to confirm, and sharing/visibility options (client recipients, internal observers, export permissions).
- Preview – provide a client-facing preview of how the decision will appear, with a toggle to view in mobile vs. desktop layouts. Include the ability to simulate client actions (view, comment, approve/deny) in the preview mode.
- Save & Publish – options to Save Draft (local/project draft) or Publish (generate a client link, trigger notifications, and lock the decision into the audit trail). Publishing should create an immutable record with a timestamp and an initial audit entry.
- UX flows must support error handling, auto-save of draft states, and recovery if a step validation fails, with clear, actionable error messaging.

Connected features and UI behavior:
- Decision Objects & Approval Workflow (Core): Each Decision Card holds options, comments, approval state, audit trail. Drafts should be editable; published decisions become part of the project’s decision log with immutable audit entries.
- Error Handling & Validation: Centralized validation across steps with user-friendly messages, inline validation, and a global error panel if needed. Include failure recovery UI (retry, revert, or discard draft).
- File Upload & Management: Support for uploading drawings, images, and attachments with per-file versioning, secure access, and retrieval. Show per-option file galleries and option-level attachments.
- CRUD Operations for Projects, Decisions, Templates, Files: Create, read, update, delete (with versioning and soft-delete support as appropriate). Ensure auditability for all CRUD actions.
- Loading / Processing Page: Global loading indicator for long-running tasks (e.g., export generation, large file uploads) with progress indication and cancellation options.
- Project Workspace: The Create Decision Page must operate within the Project Workspace context: know the project id, user roles, and client-share configuration. After publish, update the workspace’s decision list and notify relevant clients.

Visual guidance (from PROJECT CONTEXT):
- Follow the stated visual style and design system: 12-column grid, whitespace, strong typography, consistent card and navigation patterns, and status indicators.
- Use the specified color palette and typography for all components, with high-contrast text and restrained accent usage.

API integrations:
- No external APIs required for this task. All endpoints should be internal to Archject’s backend.

---

## Components to Build

1) CreateDecisionPage (Main Container)
- Type: Modal or full-page wizard with 3 steps + preview
- State: currentStep (1-4), draftDecision object, UI validation state, loading state, error messages
- Props: projectId, userId, onPublishSuccess, onCancel
- Behavior: orchestrates subcomponents, handles data aggregation and API calls

2) TemplateSelector (Step 1)
- UI: Card grid of templates with thumbnail, name, summary, and “Start from scratch” option
- Data: templates array with id, name, description, defaultOptions, preview
- Interactions: select template, preview quick teaser, choose to proceed to Step 2

3) OptionsEditor (Step 2)
- UI: List of OptionEditorItem components with add/reorder/delete
- Each OptionEditorItem supports: title, description, image/drawing file attachments, isDefault, isRecommended
- File Upload: per-option file uploader with progress, versioning
- Validation: option title required, at least one option when publishing; optional attachment size limits
- Features: drag-and-drop reordering, inline image gallery, option duplication

4) SettingsPanel (Step 3)
- UI: Form fields for
  - approvalDeadline (date/time)
  - reminders (cron-like or simple interval list: e.g., 3 days before, 1 day before)
  - clientMustTypeNameToConfirm (boolean)
  - sharingOptions: recipients (multi-select with search), internal observers, public link toggle, export permissions
- Validation: at least one client recipient if publishing; reminder times are valid
- Helpers: sample reminder presets, scheduling previews

5) PreviewPanel (Preview)
- UI: client-facing rendering of the Decision Card
- Modes: Mobile view vs Desktop view toggle
- Interactions: simulate client actions (view, comment, approve/deny) for demonstration
- Links: show the public link URI (read-only) once published
- Validation: ensure fields reflect current state (options, recipients, deadlines)

6) ActionBar (Bottom or Top)
- Buttons: Save Draft (secondary), Publish (primary), Cancel/Back
- States: disabled/enabled based on validation; show inline error summary if present
- Loading indicators on actions with progress

7) LoadingPage
- Global loading overlay with progress indicator and estimated time if available
- Used during export generation or large uploads

8) ErrorBoundary / ValidationSummary
- Centralized component to surface validation errors with actionable steps
- Persists across steps and recovers on retry

9) AssetManager (File Upload & Management)
- Per-decision and per-option file management
- Supports versioning, secure access, and retrieval
- UI: file list, thumbnail grid, version controls, delete/archive

10) AuditTrailView (optional)
- Lightweight view to display action history for the Decision Card (who changed what and when)
- Accessible from the Decision Card in Project Workspace

11) Snackbar / Toasts
- Global notifications for success/failure (Publish success, errors, reloads)

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Frameworks: React (or project’s standard), with a modular, component-based structure
- State management: useContext or a lightweight store for the multi-step form state; centralize draft data in a local state with eventual persistence to backend
- Forms: Accessible, with proper labels, ARIA attributes, and inline validation
- Drag-and-drop: Implement option reordering using a sortable list library or native drag-and-drop
- File uploads: Client-side validation for file types and sizes; chunked uploads for large files if needed; preview thumbnails for images/drawings
- API integration: Use existing project APIs for templates, decisions, files, recipients, and audit log. The page should prepare a payload that matches backend models.
- Error handling: Show user-friendly messages; provide retry and fallback UI
- Performance: Lazy-load templates and assets; avoid heavy renders; optimize large option lists
- Accessibility: Keyboard navigation, focus management, readable contrast

### Backend
- Data Models (new/extended):
  - DecisionCard
    - id, projectId, title, description, templateId (nullable), status (draft/published), createdAt, updatedAt, publishedAt
    - approvalState (pending/approved/rejected/completed), auditTrail (references to actions)
    - options: embedded or related Option items
    - recipients: list of ClientRecipient (userId or email, role)
    - reminders: array of Reminder objects (type, when, message)
    - attachments: related FileReferences with versioning
  - Option
    - id, decisionId, title, description, isDefault, isRecommended, attachments
  - FileAttachment
    - id, parentType (decision/option), parentId, filePath, version, mimeType, size, uploadedBy, uploadedAt
  - Template
    - id, name, description, defaultOptions, previewAssets
  - AuditLog
    - id, decisionId, action, performedBy, performedAt, details
  - Reminder
    - id, decisionId, type (email, platform), schedule (cron-like or relative), message
  - Recipient
    - id, projectId, contactEmail, role (client, observer)
- Endpoints (core REST or GraphQL as per project):
  - POST /projects/{projectId}/decisions (create draft from template or scratch)
  - GET /projects/{projectId}/decisions/{decisionId} (read)
  - PUT /projects/{projectId}/decisions/{decisionId} (update)
  - POST /projects/{projectId}/decisions/{decisionId}/publish (publish and create client link, notifications)
  - POST /projects/{projectId}/decisions/{decisionId}/options (add option)
  - PUT /projects/{projectId}/decisions/{decisionId}/options/{optionId} (update option)
  - DELETE /projects/{projectId}/decisions/{decisionId} (soft delete or hard delete per policy)
  - POST /files/upload (general file upload with versioning)
  - GET /files/{fileId} (secure access)
  - GET /templates (list templates)
  - POST /projects/{projectId}/decisions/{decisionId}/audit (log action)
- Validation rules:
  - Title and at least one option when publishing
  - Client recipients must be defined for publishing
  - Reminders must be valid dates/tatterns
  - File size and type restrictions
- Security:
  - Auth: ensure user has project access; role-based permissions for edit/publish
  - Ensure that client share links are protected and can be revoked
- Validation:
  - Server-side validation mirrors frontend with meaningful error messages
  - Idempotent publish endpoint to avoid duplicate client links if retried

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - Step 1 stores selected templateId or explicit scratch flag in draft DecisionCard
  - Step 2 aggregates options, attachments, and flags into draft
  - Step 3 applies settings (recipients, reminders, approval constraints)
  - Preview consumes current draft to render client view
  - Publish creates final DecisionCard with publishedAt, triggers client notification workflow and creates a stable audit trail entry
- Cross-component coordination:
  - AssetManager and OptionsEditor share a common file upload service
  - AuditTrail is appended on every state-changing action (create, update, publish, option add, deletion)
  - ErrorBoundary surfaces server-side validation errors; UI provides actionable guidance

---

## User Experience Flow
1) User selects a project in Project Workspace and clicks “Create Decision.”
2) Step 1: TemplateSelector
   - User picks a template or selects “Start from scratch.”
   - User proceeds to Step 2.
3) Step 2: OptionsEditor
   - User adds one or more options, uploads images/drawings per option, marks defaults/recommendations.
   - User can reorder options via drag-and-drop.
   - User proceeds to Step 3.
4) Step 3: SettingsPanel
   - User sets approval deadline, reminders, client typing requirement, and sharing options (recipients and access).
   - User reviews the Preview (with mobile/desktop toggle).
   - User clicks Save Draft to continue editing later, or Publish to create a client share and notify recipients.
5) Publish
   - System validates inputs; on success, creates the published DecisionCard, creates a client link, logs audit entries, and sends notifications.
   - The user is redirected to the Decision Card view in the Project Workspace and the client link is copied to clipboard or presented for sharing.
6) Post-Publish
   - User can view Audit Trail, adjust settings for ongoing reminders, or create additional decisions.
7) If any step fails, a centralized error panel presents actionable messages and recovery options (retry, edit, or discard).

